  "text": "Based on the amino acid sequence of JRFL gp140 (including the signal peptide), all but four of the sites in the untreated protein were fully or partially occupied with glycans ( Figure 7 and Table  S1 ) [CITATION_1] . The unoccupied sites were: N141, N188, N611and N637. Upon extensive deglycosylation (500 U PNGase F per 1 mg of protein), the glycans at 12 out of 23 sites were removed: N88 (C1), N135 (V1/V2), N138 (V1/V2), N156 (V1/V2), N160 (V1/V2), N187 (V1/V2), N262 (C2), N276 (C2), N356 (C3) N462 (C4), N616, and N625 ( Figure 7 ). The 10 sites on which glycosylation still remained were fractionally populated with glycans. Thus, PNGase F cleaved a fraction of the glycans at these sites, but the reaction was incomplete. Most of the conserved glycans were of the high mannose type and included those glycans involved in the 2G12 binding (N295, N332, N386) [CITATION_2] (Figure 7) . Figure 8 shows a model of JRFL gp140 Env before PNGase-F treatment ( Figure 8A ) and after PNGase-F treatment ( Figure 8B ) based on the cryo-EM structure (white mesh) of Liu et al. [CITATION_3] and specificsite glycan analysis before PNGase-F treatment [CITATION_4] and after treatment ( Figure 7 ). Red molecules indicate gp120 amino acids, blue indicates gp120 glycans, white indicates 2G12 glycans [CITATION_5] , and yellow indicates gp41 glycans. Figure 8 depicts the loss of many complex glycans on gp120 and the loss of two gp41 glycans after PGNase-F treatment.",
